England":"Risby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ellerher","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Ellerker in Brantingham (ER Yorks), recorded as  <i>Alrecher</i>, 1086 in   Domesday Book  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alliker","meanings":["English:  see  Ellerker  ."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Bern</i>,  <i>Barn</i>. In the Midlands and East Anglia this is based on the Scandinavian personal name  <i>Biǫrn</i>, anglicized as  <i>Beorn</i>; in the south-west it is from Old English  <i>Beorn</i>; both names are from a word meaning ‘warrior’. Some of the following surname bearers may alternatively belong with other senses below.","2  English: status name from Middle English  <i>barn</i> (Old Scandinavian  <i>barn</i>) ‘child’. This term is found in   Domesday Book   as a byname for men of the upper classes; it might also have had the meaning ‘young man of a prominent family’, like Middle English  <i>child</i> (  see  Child  ).","3  English: locative name, nickname for residence near or employment at a barn, Middle English  <i>bern</i> (Old English  <i>bere-ærn</i>).  See also  Barnes  . Some of the post-medieval bearers may alternatively belong with (1) or (2)."]},{"name":"Elliker","meanings":["English:  see  Ellerker  ."]},{"name":"Allaker","meanings":["English:  see  Ellerker  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Ellerher was born in Risby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 6 sons and 1 daughter with Isabel \"Elizabeth\" Hotham. He died bef